haracteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Percy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin):","nickname from Old French <i>percehaie</i> ‘pierce hedge’ (Old French <i>percer</i> ‘to pierce, penetrate’ + <i>haie</i> ‘hedge, fence’), perhaps with the sense of someone breaking into an enclosure. <i>Percehaie</i> is the name of one of the sons of the foxes Renart and Hermeline in the medieval French epic <i>Roman de Renart</i>, whose earliest known version is from the 1170s. The surname is older than that, but it may originate in a nickname for the fox as ‘enclosure piercer’, perhaps amounting to ‘chicken thief’.","habitational name from any of several places called Percy in Calvados, Eure, and Manche; William <i>de Perci</i>, the Domesday tenant-in-chief and under-tenant of Hugh, Earl of Chester, came from either Percy-en-Auge (Eure) or Percy (Manche)."],"variants":[{"name":"Piercey","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Piercy","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Pearcey","meanings":["English: variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Peercy","meanings":["English: variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Pearcy","meanings":["English: variant of   Percy  ."]}]},{"name":"Ada","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of uncertain origin; it was not in general use before the late 18th century. It may be a Latinate variant of the biblical name   Adah .  However, it has also been explained as a pet form of   Adele   and   Adelaide  , Germanic female names of which the first element is <i>adal</i> ‘noble’. It was borne by a 7th-century abbess of Saint-Julien-des-Prés at Le Mans."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":33,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Ada de Percy was born about 1226, in Topcliffe, Yorkshire, England as the daughter of Richard de Percy. She married Sir William Darrel about 1241, in Sessay, Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died on 28 April 1272, in Sessay, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 47."},"et":{"about 1226–28 April 1272":"umbes 1226–28. aprill 1272","1226–1272":"1226–1272","1218–1278":"1218–1278","1242–Female":"1242–Surnud","1244–1283":"1244–1283","1246–Male":"1246–Surnud","1181–1244":"1181–1244","1242":"1242","28 April 1272":"28. aprill 1272","1283":"1283","1272":"1272","1181":"1181","1259":"1259","1226":"1226","1246":"1246","1278":"1278","about 1226":"umbes 1226","1244":"1244","about 1246":"umbes 1246","about 1244":"umbes 1244","about 1242":"umbes 1242","about 1241":"umbes 1241","1218":"1218","Sessay, York, England":"Sessay, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Topcliffe, Yorkshire, England":"Topcliffe, Yorkshire, England","Sessay, Yorkshire, England":"Sessay, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1226–28 April 1272":"noin 1226–28. huhtikuuta 1272","1226–1272":"1226–1272","1218–1278":"1218–1278","1242–Female":"1242–Kuollut","1244–1283":"1244–1283","1246–Male":"1246–Kuollut","1181–1244":"1181–1244","1242":"1242","28 April 1272":"28. huhtikuuta 1272","1283":"1283","1272":"1272","1181":"1181","1259":"1259","1226":"1226","1246":"1246","1278":"1278","about 1226":"noin 12